<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
    <%- include('./partials/header.ejs') %>
<body>
   
    <!-- Top Nav Bar -->

    <%- include('./partials/navbar.ejs') %>

    <!-- Main Content Section -->
    <main id="types-of-blood-donation">
        <!-- Introduction -->
        <section class="donation-intro">
            <p>Blood donation is a life-saving act, and there are different ways you can contribute. Each type of donation serves a unique purpose and helps various patients. Below, youâ€™ll find information on the different types of blood donations available and how each one makes a difference.</p>
        </section>

        <!-- Whole Blood Donation -->
        <section class="donation-type">
            <div class="donation-content">
                <img src="/images/africa-humanitarian-aid-doctor-taking-care-patient.jpg" alt="Whole Blood Donation" class="donation-image">
                <div class="donation-info">
                    <h2>Whole Blood Donation</h2>
                    <p>Whole blood donation is the most common type of blood donation. It involves donating approximately one pint of blood. This type of donation can be used in its entirety or separated into red cells, plasma, and platelets to help multiple patients.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Duration: 10-15 minutes</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Frequency: Every 56 days</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Who it helps: Trauma victims, surgery patients, etc.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Platelet Donation -->
        <section class="donation-type">
            <div class="donation-content">
                <img src="/images/coronavirus-blood-samples-arrangement-lab.jpg" alt="Platelet Donation" class="donation-image">
                <div class="donation-info">
                    <h2>Platelet Donation</h2>
                    <p>Platelets are a crucial component of blood that help with clotting. Platelet donation is done through a process called apheresis, which collects only platelets and returns the remaining blood components back to the donor.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Duration: 1.5-2 hours</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Frequency: Every 7 days, up to 24 times a year</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Who it helps: Cancer patients, those undergoing organ transplants, etc.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Plasma Donation -->
        <section class="donation-type">
            <div class="donation-content">
                <img src="/images/international-nurses-day-concept.jpg" alt="Plasma Donation" class="donation-image">
                <div class="donation-info">
                    <h2>Plasma Donation</h2>
                    <p>Plasma donation, like platelet donation, is done through apheresis. Plasma is the liquid part of blood that carries cells and proteins throughout the body. It is crucial for patients with clotting disorders, burns, and other serious medical conditions.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Duration: About 1 hour</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Frequency: Every 28 days, up to 13 times a year</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Who it helps: Patients with liver disease, severe infections, burns, etc.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Double Red Cell Donation -->
        <section class="donation-type">
            <div class="donation-content">
                <img src="/images/view-hand-holding-red-heart-symbolizing-affection-feelings.jpg" alt="Double Red Cell Donation" class="donation-image">
                <div class="donation-info">
                    <h2>Double Red Cell Donation</h2>
                    <p>In a double red cell donation, a special machine is used to allow donors to safely donate two units of red cells during one donation while returning plasma and platelets to the donor. Red cells are the most commonly transfused blood component.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Duration: About 30 minutes</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Frequency: Every 112 days (4 months)</li>
                        <li><i class="icon-check"></i> Who it helps: Trauma patients, surgery patients, anemia patients, etc.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
    </main>


     <!-- Footer -->
     <%- include('./partials/footer.ejs') %>
        
    </body>
    </html>